at|^b@2^z@3|
cs|5|cp|6|fp|t|
at|
^-{  Introduction to Chapter 3  }
^-|fp||cp||n^|3|at|
In earlier chapters we have already seen several examples of signals on defense and noted how signals can help the defenders to decide which cards to play. In this chapter we will go into much more detail about what defensive signals are all about, how you can use signals to help your partner on defense, and how you can benefit from the signals that your partner makes.
|n^|3|at| 
First things first - what exactly is meant by the term signal?

|
qx|3.1|
pg| ***** 0 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ A signal is the play of a card by a defender which carries a message to his partner. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 1 ***** |


at|Let's review some of the examples of signals that we have seen so far and the messages that these signals convey to the partner of the player who makes them.

|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ When a partnership uses standard leads, every time the defense leads a suit, a signal 
 is being made. The card that is led carries a message to the partner of the player that led. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


at|For example, the lead of a Queen carries 3 possible messages: either the leader has the Jack in the suit that was led, or he has a doubleton Queen, or he has a singleton Queen. Using standard leads, the Queen is not led under any other circumstances.
|
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|
cs|2|at|
^-{ One of the important reasons to be true to the principles of standard leads is so that 
 your partner receives accurate information from the messages that your leads carry! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


at|For example, if you lead the Queen when you hold the King-Queen, your partner will be fooled!|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


tb||

At|^^^^We have seen 3 situations where a defender should play the lowest card from 2 or more equals as a signal to his partner. In each case, the message of the signal is that a higher touching card (or cards) ^*Imight^*N be held, but that a lower touching card is certainly not held. In other words, the nature of these types of signals is to ^*Ideny^*N the possession of a specific card:

|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ 1. When splitting from 2 or more equal cards as the second hand to 
 play to a trick, always play the lowest card of the group of equals. }

|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


cs|3|at|{ 2. When following suit as third hand to play to a trick,
 always play the lowest card from a group of equals. }

|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ 3. When winning a trick as the fourth hand to play to that 
 trick, always play the lowest card from a group of equals. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


at|As an example of how these plays may be useful signals, assume that a Queen is played in any of the 3 situations mentioned above. The play of the Queen conveys 2 messages to the partner of the player who played that card:

|
pg| ***** 11 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ 1. That his partner might have the King of the same suit. }

|
pg| ***** 12 ***** |


cs|1|at|{ 2. That his partner definitely does not have the Jack of the same suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


at|On many deals, the ability to draw these kinds of inferences from the cards that your partner plays will help you to place critical honor cards in the unseen hands. This will often help you to make winning decisions as a defender. |
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
There are 3 important families of signals that we have not encountered yet. All of these involve the use of spot cards to give your partner messages about the nature of your hand. The study of these 3 types of signals will be the primary focus of this chapter.

Here is a list of what these 3 types of signals are named along with a brief explanation of the type of messages that they are used to convey:

|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ 1. Attitude signals are used to tell your partner about either the 
 presence or the absence of a critical honor card in a specific suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


at|For example, a defender can use an attitude signal to give his partner a message like, "I have the @SA" or "I don't have the @HA".

|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ 2. Count signals are used to tell your partner whether you have an even 
 (2, 4, 6, or 8) or an odd (1, 3, 5, or 7) number of cards in a specific suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


at|For example, a defender can use a count signal to give his partner a message like, "I have an odd number of diamonds" or "I have an even number of clubs". 

|
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ 3. Suit preference signals are used to tell your partner that you 
 would like him to play a specific suit if he should gain the lead. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


at|For example, a defender can use a suit preference signal to give his partner a message like, "I would like you to play a spade if you gain the lead".|
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
Before we start exploring attitude, count, and suit preference signals, here are some important points that you should know about signaling in general:

|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ It is not always easy to know the type of signal that your partner is using when he plays a 
 particular spot card, but it is important for partnerships to understand each others' signals. }

|
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


at|^-For example, suppose that your partner discards the @S2. Is this an attitude signal that gives a message about his honor holding in spades? Is it a count signal that gives a message as to whether he has an even or an odd number of spades? Could it be a suit preference signal asking you to play a particular suit if you should gain the lead?

The answer is partly up to each partnership to decide for themselves. You already know that partners can make bidding agreements like, "When we open 1NT we will always have between 15 and 17 HCP". Partners can also make agreements about their signals. For example, the following is a common agreement that could be used to resolve the problem described above:

|
pg| ***** 24 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ The first discard that a player makes in a suit is an attitude signal. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 25 ***** |


at|One of the main purposes of this chapter is to come up with a series of statements like the one shown above that will constitute an effective set of agreements for your partnership. Just like in bidding, some bridge authorities have different opinions about the types of signals that ^*Ishould^*N be used in various situations. You and your partner won't go far wrong if you use the suggested signaling agreements that are presented in this chapter, but you really should discuss these important matters together in order to make sure you are on the same wavelength on defense!|
pg| ***** 26 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
Here is another important principle about signaling that you should keep in mind:

|
pg| ***** 27 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ The declarer can see the signals that the defenders make and this 
 can sometimes help the declarer more than it will help the defenders! }

|
pg| ***** 28 ***** |


at|^-You have already seen plenty of situations where a declarer faces a guess in a critical suit. If the defenders are not careful and make an attitude signal in such a suit, the declarer may pick up on this signal and be able to figure out the location of the missing honors. As a result, the declarer may find it easier to make the winning guess in this suit.

|
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


at|Similarly, if a defender uses a count signal to tell his partner if he has an even or an odd number of cards in a particular suit, the declarer will get the message as well. On some deals this information will cause the declarer to adopt a plan that he would not have considered if the count signal had not been made. 

|
pg| ***** 30 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{Defenders should be careful with their signals. Only signal if you think that the message that 
is carried by your signal will be more important to your partner than it will be to the declarer!}
^-
|
pg| ***** 31 ***** |


at|It is not always easy to know if a signal will be more helpful to your partner or to the declarer. At this early point in your career as a signaler, it is best not to worry about these issues very much. 

Just keep in mind that your partner is not the only player at the table who can see your signals and use them to help reconstruct the unseen hands. Signals are perhaps the most important tool that the defenders have, but a clever declarer can sometimes cause the defenders' signals to work against them!

|
pg| ***** 32 ***** |


qx|Atti,Attitude signals|


nt|^b@2^z@3|
cs|5|cp|6|fp|t|
at|
^-{ Attitude signals }
^-
|fp||cp||at|Attitude signals are arguably the most important type of signals that the defenders have at their disposal. Here is a reminder of the type of messages that you can convey to your partner with an attitude signal:

|
pg| ***** 33 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ Attitude signals are used to tell your partner about either the
 the presence or the absence of a critical honor card in specific suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 34 ***** |


at|Before we get into the mechanics of the attitude signal, think about the power of this concept for a minute. Spot cards (especially small ones) do not win very many tricks for the defense - they are normally used for either following suit or as discards. If it weren't for signaling, spot cards would not be very useful cards for the defenders to hold.

The concept of the signal changes this. Signals allow you to use your spot cards to tell your partner more about the layout of the unseen hands. As we have seen many times, defense becomes a whole lot easier when the defenders are able to figure out what the other players were dealt! 

Attitude signals allow the defenders to resolve an important part of the mystery of what each player was dealt. These signals give the defenders the ability to use their spot cards to tell each other about the location of important honor cards. 

There are many deals where the defenders can use the information they learn from their partners' attitude signals to help them figure out the most effective suits to lead or cards to play.

|
pg| ***** 35 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
Here is the basic idea behind how attitude signals work:

|cs|2|at|^-{ Follow suit with or discard a high card to show that you have a critical honor in that suit. 
 Follow suit with or discard a low card to deny that you have a critical honor in that suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 36 ***** |


at|In other words, a high card carries the message that you like the suit that the high card belongs to. A low card carries the message that you don't like the suit that the low card belongs to.

The big question is, when should your partner interpret a high card or a low card that you play as an attitude signal? There is no simple answer to that question. The best we can do is state a few general circumstances in which the card that you play should usually be interpreted as an attitude signal. One of these situations was mentioned already:

|
pg| ***** 37 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ The first discard that a player makes in a suit should be interpreted as an attitude signal. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 38 ***** |


at|Here are a couple of other situations where it is a good idea to signal your attitude:

|
pg| ***** 39 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ When your partner leads an honor card, you should usually give him an attitude signal. }

|
pg| ***** 40 ***** |


cs|4|at|{ When your partner leads to a trick and the second hand to play appears to be 
 winning that trick, it is usually correct to give your partner an attitude signal. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 41 ***** |


at|Don't be concerned if these principles seem very abstract right now. They will make more sense when you see them applied in the card combinations and example deals that follow. |
pg| ***** 42 ***** |


st||md|2,sakt4|ha|y|sv||



nt|^b@2^z@3Here is an example of the power of attitude signals. Suppose that you are sitting West and that South is the declarer in a trump contract. Spades is a side suit and you select the @SA as your opening lead. Recall that the Ace is the standard lead from a holding that is headed by the Ace-King. |
pg| ***** 43 ***** |


