|
pg| ***** 337 ***** |


cs|4|at|{ 2. When your partner leads to a trick and the second hand to play appears to be 
 winning that trick, it is usually correct to give your partner an attitude signal. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 338 ***** |


at|In general it is easy to know whether to give an encouraging or a discouraging attitude signal in the first case described above. For example, if you partner leads a King against a trump contract, you know he has the Queen of the same suit. The Ace and the Jack of that suit will be critical cards and you should show encouragement only if you were dealt one of these cards.

|
pg| ***** 339 ***** |


at|If, however, your partner leads a spot card and the dummy wins the Ace in that suit, it is not always easy to know if you should encourage or discourage when your highest card in the suit is the Jack. 

If your partner's lead was from a suit headed by the King or a suit with no honor cards at all, he will want you to discourage when holding only the Jack, but if your partner led from a suit headed by the Queen, your Jack will be an important card for him to know about. In this case it may be right for you to encourage when you hold the Jack of the suit that your partner led.

|
pg| ***** 340 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ There are no magic formulas to tell you when to encourage and when to discourage. 
 For guidance, consider factors like your own hand, the dummy's hand, and the bidding! }

|
pg| ***** 341 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
In the examples of attitude signals that we have seen so far, there was no way for you to consider factors like your own hand, the dummy's hand, or the bidding (because so far the only attitude signals that we have seen were from simple card combinations as opposed to entire deals).

That is about to change and this is probably just as well since you are no doubt getting pretty sick of looking at card combinations!

|
pg| ***** 342 ***** |


at|We are about to look at attitude signals in the context of an entire deal. This is actually necessary because there is more than one suit involved in the third main type of situation where attitude signals should be used:

|
pg| ***** 343 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{3. The first discard that a player makes in a suit should be intended as an attitude signal.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 344 ***** |


at|Up until now, when you have had to make discards as a defender, you may have thought about this process as no more than an opportunity to get rid of some of your useless small cards. 

Now that you have seen some examples of how attitude signals can help the defense, you have no doubt realized that small cards are not so useless after all! By carefully selecting the specific cards that you discard and the order in which you discard them, you can tell your partner a lot about the cards you were dealt. 

That in turn will help him to defend more accurately later in the play. 

|
pg| ***** 345 ***** |


at|Before we go on to look at some complete deals in which discards act as attitude signals, here is an another point about these kinds of signals that you should keep in mind:

|
pg| ***** 346 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{Attitude signals relate to the suit of the signal (not the suit that was led). In prior examples
 these suits were the same, but when a discard is an attitude signal they will not be the same! }
|
