nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|5|cp|6|tb|y|fp|t|at|
^-{  Attitude signals - Review and Exercises  }
^-|fp||at|
|cp||at|This chapter is all about signaling on defense. So far we have focused almost exclusively on one particular type of signal - the attitude signal, but before we looked at attitude signals in detail we made some observations of signals in general. First and foremost, we defined what is meant by the term signal:

|
pg| ***** 447 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ A signal is the play of a card by the defender that carries a message to his partner. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 448 ***** |


at|We then considered some examples of signals that we have already encountered in earlier chapters. You may not have thought of these sorts of plays as signals at the time, but that is exactly what they are. Much of the first chapter of this program was devoted to a particular type of signal - the signals that we make when we decide which card to lead from a particular holding:

|
pg| ***** 449 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ When a partnership uses standard leads, every time the defense leads a suit, a signal 
 is being made. The card that is led carries a message to the partner of the player that led. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 450 ***** |


at|By thinking about standard leads as a type of signal, it becomes all the more clear why a partnership can benefit from making such leads:
^-
|
pg| ***** 451 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ One of the important reasons to be true to the principle of standard leads is so that 
 your partner receives accurate information from the messages that your leads carry! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 452 ***** |


at|Your partner is on your side - the last thing you want to do is give him a false message!

|
pg| ***** 453 ***** |


tb|n|

nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|We then noted that we had already seen 3 other situations where the card that a defender plays can be interpreted as a signal:

|
pg| ***** 454 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ 1. When splitting from 2 or more equal cards as the second hand to 
 play to a trick, always play the lowest card of the group of equals. }

|
pg| ***** 455 ***** |


cs|1|at|{ 2. When following suit as third hand to play to a trick,
 always play the lowest card from a group of equals. }

|
pg| ***** 456 ***** |


cs|4|at|{ 3. When winning a trick as the fourth hand to play to that 
 trick, always play the lowest card from a group of equals. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 457 ***** |


at|Whenever a defender plays the correct card in any of these situations, his partner knows that he may have a higher touching card (or cards), but that he certainly does not have any lower touching cards. Such plays carry messages and that's what makes them signals!

Signals can do wonders for the defenders, but there is a danger in using signals as well:

|
pg| ***** 458 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ The declarer can see the signals that the defenders make and this 
 can sometimes help the declarer more than it will help the defenders! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 459 ***** |


at|The only way for the defenders to avoid this danger is to keep the following in mind:
|n#|8|
pg| ***** 460 ***** |


cs|1|At|^-{Defenders should be careful with their signals. Only signal if you think that the message that 
is carried by your signal will be more important to your partner than it will be to the declarer!}

|
pg| ***** 461 ***** |


cs|1|

nt|^b@2^z@3
Here are some more general principles about signaling that we have encountered:

|
pg| ***** 462 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Always signal with the loudest card that you can afford! If you follow this practice it will be
 easier for your partner to understand the message that your signal was intended to deliver. }

|
pg| ***** 463 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ Sometimes a defender is not dealt the spot cards to convey the message that he would 
like to. He can only try his best and hope that his partner is able to work out the position. }

|
pg| ***** 464 ***** |


cs|3|at|{ Signaling is a critical part of defense, but it is not as critical as winning tricks! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 465 ***** |


at|We then went on to consider the 3 new kinds of signals to be introduced in this chapter and the types of messages that these signals convey:

|
pg| ***** 466 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ 1. Attitude signals are used to tell your partner about either the 
 presence or the absence of a critical honor card in a specific suit. }

|
pg| ***** 467 ***** |


cs|4|at|{ 2. Count signals are used to tell your partner whether you have an even 
 (2, 4, 6, or 8) or an odd (1, 3, 5, or 7) number of cards in a specific suit. }

|
pg| ***** 468 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ 3. Suit preference signals are used to tell your partner that you 
 would like him to play a specific suit if he should gain the lead. }

|
pg| ***** 469 ***** |


